19. osa sum. This passage is quoted by both Priscian, 9. 4. p. 517, and by Nonius p. 148, for this auxiliary form of odi, the only passage in classical Latin where it occurs, though perosus and exosus are both usual.

20. Heia autem inimicos? ‘how now? enemies, pray?⁷ Heia is here used as an expostulatory particle. Pers. 2. 2. 30 Heia! ‘Come‚ come‚’ to which Sophoclidisca replies Beicz! ‘Hum, hum.' The general use of heia is a particle of en· couragement, of oheering, or urging a person on, ‘on with you.' If we urge a person on to some better course, the particle becomes expostulatory, so that the two usages har· monize. . We are reminded of Shakespeare, Pericles Act 4.
